definition.value: Excessive action of the lateral rectus muscle caused by increased innervation typically as a consequence of palsy or limitation to the ipsilateral antagonist or contralateral synergist.
Excessive action of the medial rectus muscle caused by increased innervation typically as a consequence of palsy or limitation to the ipsilateral antagonist or contralateral synergist.
Mechanical limitation of the range of movement of the lateral rectus muscle.
Any structural anomaly of the posterior circulating artery (PCOM).
A widening (ballooning) localized in the wall of the posterior communicating artery.
A type of cyclophoria (latent strabismus in which the occluded eye wheel-rotates on dissociation.) in which the upper poles of the globes are rotated outward (laterally) to each other.
An abnormality in voluntary or involuntary eyelid movements or their control.
Astigmatism with more plus power on the horizontal meridian.
A type of astigmatism related to an irregular shape of the lens.
A type of astigmatism in which the principle meridians are not 90 degrees apart and which is associated with loss of vision.
A decrease below the normal concentration of glycerol in the blood.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of glycerol in the blood.
The course a disease typically takes from its onset, progression in time, and eventual resolution or death of the affected individual.
Any functional anomaly of the vocal cord.
Bleeding within the fundus of the eye.
